      'A balance sheet is a snapshot of what a company owns (assets) and owes (liabilities) at a single point in time. The difference between the two is shareholder equity — the value left for owners after creditors are paid. The whole document fits on one page, which is why it\'s the fastest way to gauge financial health.',
      'Two ratios do most of the work. Debt-to-equity (D/E) tells you how much the company runs on borrowed money versus owner capital. Above 1.0 is risky for most sectors but normal for capital-intensive ones (airlines, banks, telecom). Current ratio (current assets ÷ current liabilities) tells you whether they can pay this year\'s bills. Below 1.0 is a yellow flag.',
      'Sector context is everything. A bank with D/E of 9 is normal — banks are leverage machines. An airline with D/E of 1.4 is normal — planes are expensive. The same number in different sectors tells very different stories. Always compare a company to its peers, not to an arbitrary "good" number.',
